&lt;h2 id=&#34;simulation-summary&#34;&gt;Simulation Summary
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parameter Sampling&lt;/strong&gt;: Sample all random variables to generate parameters&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Single Turbine Simulation&lt;/strong&gt;: Execute all above processes for one turbine until reaching service life&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iterative Convergence&lt;/strong&gt;: Repeat iterations until convergence (converges to stable values after 30,000 iterations, all simulations performed 50,000 iterations)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&#34;simulation-results-and-performance-indicators&#34;&gt;Simulation Results and Performance Indicators
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;h2 id=&#34;wind-turbine-availability&#34;&gt;Wind Turbine Availability
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;key-findings&#34;&gt;Key Findings
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Shortening AS Intervals&lt;/strong&gt;: Shortening adjacent Advanced Service (AS) time intervals can improve wind turbine availability, but is still not as effective as using any monitoring system&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Monitoring System Advantages&lt;/strong&gt;: Using SCADA or CMS monitoring systems can significantly improve availability&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dual System Effects&lt;/strong&gt;: When performing frequent AS, combining two monitoring systems may lead to decreased availability, because the downtime for repairing the turbine after damage detection becomes longer&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
