&lt;h1 id=&#34;research-conclusions-and-practical-implications&#34;&gt;Research Conclusions and Practical Implications
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;h2 id=&#34;main-conclusions&#34;&gt;Main Conclusions
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Value of Monitoring Systems&lt;/strong&gt;: Both dedicated CMS and SCADA systems can significantly improve wind turbine availability, but SCADA, as a lower-cost alternative, has considerable economic benefits&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Maintenance Strategy Optimization&lt;/strong&gt;: Condition-Based Maintenance (CBM) combined with appropriate monitoring systems can maximize availability while controlling costs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;System Synergy Effects&lt;/strong&gt;: The synergistic use of SCADA and CMS may produce diminishing marginal returns in some cases, requiring trade-offs between additional detection capabilities and downtime costs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cost-Effectiveness Balance&lt;/strong&gt;: COA indicators show that the optimal strategy is not always the most advanced monitoring system, but rather the best balance point between cost and benefit&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
